<subsection xml:id="subsec-types-of-angles">
    <title>Types of Angles</title>
    <p>
        Angles are classified according to their sizes. 
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Right Angle</term> - A perfect <m>90^\circ</m> angle, just like the corners of a square or the edges of a notebook.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Acute Angle</term> - This angle is less than <m>90^\circ</m>. It looks small and sharp, like the tip of a pencil! 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Obtuse Angle</term> - This angle is greater than <m>90^\circ</m> but less than <m>180^\circ</m>. It looks wide and open, like a door halfway open.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Reflex Angle</term> - This is an angle that is greater than <m>180^\circ</m> but less than <m>360^\circ</m>. 
                    It appears when two lines extend beyond a straight angle, forming a large outward bend.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Straight Angle</term> - A <m>180^\circ</m> angle, which forms a straight lineâ€”like the horizon!
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>              
    </p>
    
